    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading a manual for a cessna 172 and saw stuff about the pitot tube. can u explain how it actually works to measure airspeed? and why is it such a big deal if it gets blocked up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The pitot tube is a critical component in measuring airspeed on an aircraft like the Cessna 172. It works by measuring the dynamic pressure of the air, which is the pressure difference between the front and rear of the tube due to air moving over and under it. This pressure difference is related to the airspeed, and by knowing the temperature and air density, pilots can calculate the true airspeed ( TAS ) accurately. If the pitot tube becomes blocked, it can cause inaccurate airspeed readings, leading to potential issues with flight control, navigation, and even safety.",
      "source": "target",
